<P>
World's top scientists say global warming 'very likely' man-made,
will last for centuries
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The warning from a top panel of international scientists
is blunt and dire: "warming of the climate system is
unequivocal," the cause is "very likely" man-made, and the menace
will "continue for centuries." In a 21-page report on why the
planet is warming, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change
places the onus on governments to stop prevaricating and to take
action.  CHANGE. Developing. By Seth Borenstein. AP Photos. AP
Graphic CLIMATE REPORT. With excerpts, main points.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- CHANGE-WORLD VIEW. PARIS -- The report's bleak outlook brings
warnings from around the world that drastic, rapid change is
needed -- not least from the United States. Developing. By John
Leicester.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo takes 1st steps toward possible statehood under newly
unveiled U.N. roadmap
</P>
<P>
PRISTINA, Serbia -- Kosovo takes its first tentative steps on the
road to possible statehood as a U.N. envoy unveils his long-
awaited blueprint for the future of the tense Serbian province.
The plan's architect, former Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
calls the plan a compromise that still could change, but Kosovo
seems destined to gain conditional, internationally supervised
independence.  Developing. By Garentina Kraja. AP Photos. With
glance, chronology.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- NEXT? BELGRADE, Serbia -- The unveiling of the U.N. plan
launches a process to resolve a decades-old crisis in one of
Europe's worst hotbeds of ethnic tensions. By 1600GMT. By Dusan
Stojanovic.
</P>
<P>
-- BELGRADE, Serbia -- Western officials support Ahtisaari as he
unveils a proposal for the future of Kosovo, and urge Serbia and
Kosovo Albanians to show "flexibility." By 1600GMT. By Jovana
Gec.
</P>
<P>
Hamas announces truce deal; 10 killed in Gaza violence.
</P>
<P>
GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip -- A Hamas spokesman announces that a new
cease-fire agreement has been reached between the Islamic
militant group and the rival Fatah movement. Meanwhile, Fatah
fighters storm a Hamas-affiliated university for a second time,
setting buildings on fire -- dealing a sharp blow to Hamas'
prestige and threatening to escalate an already raging battle
between the two factions in the Gaza Strip.  Developing. By
Ibrahim Barzak. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- RAMALLAH, West Bank -- Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas
will meet with Hamas' top leader in Saudi Arabia next week in
another effort to negotiate a national unity government
agreement, an Abbas aide says. Moved. By Mohammed Daraghmeh.
</P>
<P>
-- WASHINGTON -- World powers have largely abandoned hope that
Hamas radicals will drop anti-Israel positions that have riven
the Palestinian leadership and led to a cutoff of direct
international aid. Moved; will be led following 1815GMT briefing.
By Anne Gearan.
</P>
<P>
MIDDLE EAST:
</P>
<P>
U.S. military investigating reports of a helicopter down north of
Baghdad
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD, Iraq -- Gunmen assassinate an outspoken Sunni critic of
al-Qaida in Iraq as he leaves his home for noon prayers, and U.S.
kill 18 insurgents in a late night battle in another Sunni city.
The violence underscores the ongoing threat posed by Sunni
insurgents outside Baghdad at a time when attention is focused on
sectarian bloodletting in the capital.  Developing. By Kim Gamel.
AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of demonstrators clash with authorities after 3
activists arrested
</P>
<P>
MANAMA, Bahrain -- Several hundred demonstrators clash with
authorities who fired tear gas and rubber bullets at the crowds
after police arrested three prominent human rights activists in
separate raids in the capital, local rights groups say.  ARREST.
Moved. By Reem Khalifa.
</P>
<P>
EUROPE:
</P>
<P>
Diplomats: Iran puts down piping, cables for underground uranium
enrichment plant
</P>
<P>
VIENNA, Austria -- Hundreds of workers in Iran have begun putting
down piping and electric cables for its underground uranium
enrichment plant, diplomats say, moving ahead quickly on a
program that many countries fear could be used to make nuclear
arms.  Moved. By George Jahn.
</P>
<P>
3 linked to Moscow subway bombings get life in prison
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A Russian court sentences three people to life in
prison for their role in a pair of Moscow subway bombings in 2004
that killed nearly 50 people, a court spokeswoman says.  BLASTS.
Moved.
</P>
<P>
Blair says 'wrong' to step down before police conclude cash-for-
honors probe
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair breaks his silence a
week after police questioned him for a second time over
allegations that political honors were traded for cash, insisting
that he will not step down before the inquiry concludes.
SCANDAL. Moved. By D'Arcy Doran. AP Photos planned.
</P>
<P>
Rome subway planners struggle to avoid collision between past and
future
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The perennial tug of war between preserving ancient
treasures and developing much-needed infrastructure is moving
underground as Rome mobilizes archaeologists to probe beneath the
Eternal City in preparation for a new subway line.  ARCHAEOLOGY.
Moved. By Ariel David. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
AFRICA:
</P>
<P>
Chinese president tells Sudan counterpart he must do more for
peace in Darfur
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM, Sudan -- Chinese President Hu Jintao urges Sudan's Omar
al-Bashir to work harder to bring more Darfur rebels into the
peace process, a Sudanese official tells the AP.  Developing. By
Alfred de Montesquiou. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Explosion at Islamic school wounds 7, say witnesses
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU, Somalia -- An explosion at an Islamic school for women
and girls in the capital wounds at least seven people, witnesses
say, after a night of some of the worst violence in Mogadishu
since the interim government took control from an Islamic
movement.  Moved. By Mohamed Olad Hassan. AP Photos NAI101-102.
</P>
<P>
ASIA:
</P>
<P>
Pakistan to fence border with Afghanistan, admits some troops
have let militants cross
</P>
<P>
RAWALPINDI, Pakistan -- Pakistan will erect fencing to reinforce
parts of its porous mountain border with Afghanistan, President
Gen. Pervez Musharraf says, while acknowledging for the first
time that some outgunned Pakistani frontier guards have allowed
militants to cross.  FENCE. Moved. By Matthew Pennington. AP
Photos ISL101-104.
</P>
<P>
ALSO:
</P>
<P>
-- RAWALPINDI, Pakistan -- Musharraf says relations have never
been better between Pakistan and archrival India, which have
fought three wars since their independence from Britain 60 years
ago.  Moved. By Matthew Pennington.
</P>
<P>
U.S., North Korea relations improving ahead of nuclear talks,
South Korean official says
</P>
<P>
SEOUL, South Korea -- The U.S. and North Korea have softened
their positions over a bitter row about the North's nuclear
program, a South Korean official says ahead of the expected
resumption of arms talks later this month.  Lead moved. By Jae-
soon Chang. AP Photo TOK104.
</P>
<P>
LATIN AMERICA:
</P>
<P>
Asylum-seeking Cuban doctors mired in legal limbo
</P>
<P>
BOGOTA, Colombia -- At least 38 Cuban doctors who defected from a
medical mission to Venezuela are stuck in Colombia -- which has
refused them refugee status -- awaiting word on whether they'll
be allowed into the United States. A new U.S. policy that took
effect in August was supposed to make it easier for them to
obtain asylum.  DEFECTORS. By 1800GMT. By Joshua Goodman. AP
Photos.
</P>
<P>
NORTH AMERICA:
</P>
<P>
Turner CEO apologizes for Boston electronic signs security scare
</P>
<P>
BOSTON -- Turner Broadcasting System apologizes to Boston-area
residents for a security scare that had bomb squads checking out
electronic signs that were part of a nationwide marketing
campaign for its subsidiary Cartoon Network.  DEVICES. Moved. By
Denise Lavoie and Jay Lindsay. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
BUSINESS &amp; FINANCE:
</P>
<P>
NYSE fourth-quarter swings to profit after Archipelago
acquisition
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The New York Stock Exchange, the world's biggest
financial market, says its fourth quarter showed a profit
following its acquisition of electronic market Archipelago.
Moved.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson says 4th-quarter profit rose 13 percent
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, Sweden -- Ericsson AB, the world's largest maker of
wireless networks, says that fourth-quarter profit rose 13
percent, boosted by strong sales and its recent integration of
British fixed telecom networks company Marconi.  Moved. By Louise
Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
Macau bank says HSBC helped it authenticate U.S. dollar deposits
by North Korea
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- HSBC, one of the world's biggest banks, helped
screen large deposits of cash from North Korean customers for a
Macau bank accused by the U.S. of helping Pyongyang distribute
counterfeit money, a lawyer for the bank tells U.S.
investigators.  KOREA-HSBC. Moved. By William Foreman.
</P>
<P>
Nissan's profit tumbles 22.6 percent in 3rd quarter; cuts profit
forecast
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Automaker Nissan Motor Co. says profit tumbled 22.6
percent in the October-December quarter amid rising commodity
costs, tougher competition and softening sales.  Moved. By Hans
Greimel.
</P>
